		=09
                 	CALL FOR PAPERS
	            Fifth International Conference on
   Formal Structures for Computation and Deduction (FSCD 2020)
                 June 29 =E2=80=93 July 5, 2020, Paris, France
	         	       http://fscd2020.org/ =
<http://fscd2020.org/>
=20
IMPORTANT DATES
---------------
All deadlines are midnight anywhere-on-earth (AoE); late submissions =
will not be considered.
       Abstract:        February 6, 2020
       Submission:   February 9, 2020=09
       Rebuttal:        March 27-29, 2020
       Notification:    April 13, 2020
       Final version: April 27, 2020

INVITED SPEAKERS
----------------
- Ren=C3=A9 Thiemann:  FSCD-IJCAR joint speaker
  (http://cl-informatik.uibk.ac.at/users/thiemann/ =
<http://cl-informatik.uibk.ac.at/users/thiemann/>)
- John Harrison:     FSCD-IJCAR joint speaker
  (https://www.cl.cam.ac.uk/~jrh13/ <https://www.cl.cam.ac.uk/~jrh13/>)=20=

- Brigitte Pienta
  (https://www.cs.mcgill.ca/~bpientka/ =
<https://www.cs.mcgill.ca/~bpientka/>)
- Andrew Pitts
  (https://www.cl.cam.ac.uk/~amp12/ <https://www.cl.cam.ac.uk/~amp12/>)
- Simona Ronchi della Rocca
  (http://www.di.unito.it/~ronchi/ <http://www.di.unito.it/~ronchi/>)  =20=


FSCD (http://fscdconference.org/ <http://fscdconference.org/> ) covers =
all aspects of formal structures for computation=20
and deduction from theoretical foundations to applications. Building on =
two communities, RTA
(Rewriting Techniques and Applications) and TLCA (Typed Lambda Calculi =
and Applications),=20
FSCD embraces their core topics and broadens their scope to closely =
related areas in logics,=20
models of computation, semantics and verification in new challenging =
areas.=20

The suggested, but not exclusive, list of topics for submission is:

1. Calculi: Rewriting systems (string, term, higher-order, graph, =
conditional, modulo, infinitary, etc.);
    Lambda calculus; Logics (first-order, higher-order, equational, =
modal, linear, classical, constructive, etc.);=20
    Proof theory (natural deduction, sequent calculus, proof nets, =
etc.); Type theory and logical frameworks;=20
    Homotopy type theory; Quantum calculi.

2. Methods in Computation and Deduction: Type systems (poly- morphism, =
dependent, recursive, intersection, session, etc.);=20
    Induction, coinduction; Matching, unification, completion, order- =
ings; Strategies (normalization, completeness, etc.);=20
    Tree automata; Model building and model checking; Proof search and =
theorem proving;=20
    Constraint solving and decision procedures.

3. Semantics: Operational semantics and abstract machines; Game =
Semantics and applications;=20
    Domain theory and categorical models; Quantitative models (timing, =
probabilities, etc.);=20
    Quantum computation and emerging models in computation.

4. Algorithmic Analysis and Transformations of Formal Systems: Type =
Inference and type checking;=20
    Abstract Interpretation; Complexity analysis and implicit =
computational complexity;=20
    Checking termination, confluence, derivational complexity and =
related properties; Symbolic computation.

5. Tools and Applications: Programming and proof environments; =
Verification tools;
    Proof assistants and interactive theorem provers; Applications in =
industry;=20
    Applications of formal sys- tems in other sciences.

6. Semantics and Verification in new challenging areas: Certification; =
Security; Blockchain protocols;=20
    Data Bases; Deep learning and machine learning algorithms; Planning.

PUBLICATION
--------------------
The proceedings will be published as an electronic volume in the Leibniz =
International
Proceedings in Informatics (LIPIcs) of Schloss Dagstuhl. All LIPIcs =
proceedings are open access.

SPECIAL ISSUE
----------------------
Authors of selected papers will be invited to submit an extended version =
to a special issue of=20
Logical Methods in Computer Science.

SUBMISSION GUIDELINES=20
--------------------------------------
Submissions can be made in two categories. Regular research papers are =
limited to 15 pages,=20
excluding references. They must present original research which is =
unpublished and not submitted elsewhere.=20
Proofs and other technical details that do not fit within the page limit =
can be submitted as an appendix (up to 5 pages).=20
The appendix will be consulted at the discretion of the reviewers. =
Therefore, submissions must be self-contained within=20
the respective page limit; the additional material should not be =
necessary to assess the merits of a submission.=20
System descriptions are limited to 15 pages, excluding references. They =
must present new software tools,=20
or significantly new versions of such tools, in which FSCD topics play =
an important role. An archive of the code=20
with instructions on how to install and run the tool must be submitted. =
In addition, a webpage where the system can be=20
experimented with should be provided.=20
Complete instructions on submitting a paper can be found on the =
conference web site.

BEST PAPER AWARD BY JUNIOR RESEARCHERS
--------------------------------------
The program committee will select a paper in which at least one author =
is a junior researcher,=20
i.e. either a student or whose PhD award date is less than three years =
from the first day of the meeting.=20
Other authors should declare to the PC Chair that at least 50% of =
contribution is made by the junior researcher(s).

